WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.520
[Amit Varma]: One of my bugbears about India is that if you stop someone on the street and ask for

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:12.000
[Amit Varma]: directions, they will give you directions.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:15.560
[Amit Varma]: They may never have heard of the place you're trying to reach, but directions they will

00:00:15.560 --> 00:00:16.560
[Amit Varma]: give.

00:00:16.560 --> 00:00:20.020
[Amit Varma]: Go straight, turn right at the banyan tree, turn left at the barbershop, then right again

00:00:20.020 --> 00:00:24.360
[Amit Varma]: at the podcasting studio, then straight until you hit a dead end, climb the wall in front

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:28.960
[Amit Varma]: of you, jump into the cesspool on the other side, and as Lord Yama comes to take your

00:00:28.960 --> 00:00:32.080
[Amit Varma]: soul away, ask him, he will know.

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:36.480
[Amit Varma]: Social media is a bit like that, except that no one asks for directions, and still people

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:37.480
[Amit Varma]: give.

00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:41.160
[Amit Varma]: It's imperative on social media to have an opinion on everything.

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:43.560
[Amit Varma]: On Monday, you're an expert in pandemics.

00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:45.840
[Amit Varma]: On Tuesday, you're an expert in foreign policy.

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:50.160
[Amit Varma]: On Wednesday, you will lecture a rocket scientist on how a rocket should be designed.

00:00:50.160 --> 00:00:55.160
[Amit Varma]: Actually, the thing is, in the hard sciences, while you do have outlier cases of idiots

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:59.320
[Amit Varma]: lecturing Nobel Prize winners, you don't see so much gyan being given.

00:00:59.320 --> 00:01:03.680
[Amit Varma]: But in fields like economics and foreign policy, everyone is a pandit.

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:07.720
[Amit Varma]: People who comment on economics make the same standard set of mistakes.

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:10.200
[Amit Varma]: They care about intentions instead of outcomes.

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:12.560
[Amit Varma]: They treat the world as a zero-sum game.

00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:16.520
[Amit Varma]: They think with a top-down engineering mindset because that is all their peanut brains can

00:01:16.520 --> 00:01:17.640
[Amit Varma]: comprehend.

00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:22.240
[Amit Varma]: And in foreign policy, we make the mistake of thinking in terms of principles instead

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:24.380
[Amit Varma]: of interests and levers.

00:01:24.380 --> 00:01:28.000
[Amit Varma]: For the last couple of weeks, everyone on Twitter has been a foreign policy expert.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.600
[Amit Varma]: I'm kind of glad these recent elections happened, as that diverted attention from Russia and

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:33.600
[Amit Varma]: Ukraine.

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:37.280
[Amit Varma]: One random fellow started lecturing me, and this is offline, not on Twitter.

00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:41.920
[Amit Varma]: One random fellow started lecturing me on Ukraine, and I deftly diverted him by asking

00:01:41.920 --> 00:01:46.320
[Amit Varma]: for his opinion on vote distribution in Uttarakhand.

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:47.880
[Amit Varma]: So much gyan everywhere.

00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:48.880
[Amit Varma]: So much gyan.

00:01:48.880 --> 00:01:57.440
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:57.440 --> 00:01:58.440
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:58.440 --> 00:02:04.520
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Barma.

00:02:04.520 --> 00:02:05.880
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen.

00:02:05.880 --> 00:02:10.680
[Amit Varma]: I was in Bangalore when Russia invaded Ukraine, recording seven episodes of the show in eight

00:02:10.680 --> 00:02:11.680
[Amit Varma]: days.

00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:14.800
[Amit Varma]: You've already heard two of them with Ram Guha and Dhani Rajendran.

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:18.960
[Amit Varma]: And while I bumped into my friends Pranay Kota Sane and Nitin Pai over there, it didn't

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:21.960
[Amit Varma]: strike me that maybe we should chat about Russia and Ukraine.

00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:26.920
[Amit Varma]: It was when I got back to Mumbai that I thought, hey, why not do an episode where we use the

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:31.520
[Amit Varma]: Russia-Ukraine conflict to illustrate basic principles of foreign policy.

00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:35.600
[Amit Varma]: Most of us, when we approach a new subject, we get confused by all the information around

00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:36.600
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:02:36.600 --> 00:02:41.580
[Amit Varma]: It helps to understand it from first principles, to build a framework or a lens through which

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:43.420
[Amit Varma]: we can view the problem.

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:47.600
[Amit Varma]: My first instinct when Russia invaded Ukraine, and probably yours as well, was to condemn

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:51.640
[Amit Varma]: Russia and Vladimir Putin for the needless violence.

00:02:51.640 --> 00:02:53.040
[Amit Varma]: Now the questions come up.

00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:54.480
[Amit Varma]: How should India react?

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:55.880
[Amit Varma]: What caused the conflict?

00:02:55.880 --> 00:02:57.500
[Amit Varma]: What are the dynamics in play here?

00:02:57.500 --> 00:02:59.340
[Amit Varma]: What are Europe's pulls and pressures?

00:02:59.340 --> 00:03:02.040
[Amit Varma]: What mistakes has the US made in this conflict?

00:03:02.040 --> 00:03:03.920
[Amit Varma]: What will China take away from this?

00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:07.680
[Amit Varma]: And in general, how should we look at international relations?

00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:10.920
[Amit Varma]: I thought Pranay and Nitin would be the perfect people to talk about this.

00:03:10.920 --> 00:03:14.440
[Amit Varma]: And hey, they've been educating people on this for over a decade.

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:19.440
[Amit Varma]: Nitin started the Takshashila Institution in Bangalore many, many years ago, and every

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:25.440
[Amit Varma]: year these guys teach courses on public policy and foreign policy to over a thousand people

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:26.440
[Amit Varma]: every year.

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:28.240
[Amit Varma]: Their faculty is incredible.

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:32.120
[Amit Varma]: And if you are interested in the subject for this episode, you might want to sign up for

00:03:32.120 --> 00:03:37.320
[Amit Varma]: the May cohort of Takshashila's GCCP course in Defense and Foreign Affairs, which introduces

00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:41.120
[Amit Varma]: students to the role of military and economic power in global affairs.

00:03:41.120 --> 00:03:43.360
[Amit Varma]: I'll give the link for it in the show notes.

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:47.680
[Amit Varma]: We recorded this episode remotely, and Nitin had to leave in a couple of hours, so he's

00:03:47.680 --> 00:03:49.480
[Amit Varma]: only there for the first half.

00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:52.280
[Amit Varma]: In this first half, we freewheel through a bunch of topics.

00:03:52.280 --> 00:03:56.440
[Amit Varma]: And in the second half, Pranay and I dig deeper in a more systematic way.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:03:59.360
[Amit Varma]: But don't think of this episode as an explainer.

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:05.000
[Amit Varma]: It works much better in provoking thought, in showing you new pathways into the subject,

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:09.600
[Amit Varma]: in opening up rabbit holes to you, which I hope you'll use the show notes to explore.

00:04:09.600 --> 00:04:15.240
