02:04:45.440 --> 02:04:51.040
[Amit Varma]: And now we'll kind of continue talking about principles of foreign policy and you know,

02:04:51.040 --> 02:04:56.480
[Amit Varma]: how we can look at them through the Russia-Ukraine conflict or rather through the Russian invasion

02:04:56.480 --> 02:05:01.520
[Amit Varma]: of Ukraine. So Pranay, you know, we were chatting about economic sanctions before the break.

02:05:01.520 --> 02:05:06.080
[Amit Varma]: Give me, you know, we speak about different kinds of leverage about different kinds of power.

02:05:06.080 --> 02:05:11.120
[Amit Varma]: You know, when we talk of economic power per se, you know, what exactly do we mean by it? And what

02:05:11.120 --> 02:05:16.560
[Amit Varma]: is it good for? Like, I've, you know, I think Nitin was the first person from whom I read the

02:05:16.560 --> 02:05:22.800
[Amit Varma]: formulation to the effect of a rising GDP is the best foreign policy, right? Obviously referring to

02:05:22.800 --> 02:05:28.480
[Amit Varma]: how economic growth increases your leverage in the world and economics therefore matters. So

02:05:28.480 --> 02:05:33.200
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit about this that you know, why does it matter beyond the obvious sense that

02:05:33.200 --> 02:05:37.760
[Amit Varma]: hey, we are a bigger market for everyone and we have more goods and services to export and all of

02:05:37.760 --> 02:05:43.040
[Amit Varma]: that. Beyond that sense, you know, why does it matter? What is it good for? How do we use it in

02:05:43.040 --> 02:05:49.680
[Guest 2]: foreign policy? Yeah, right. So I guess like the one central lesson of one of the lessons of this

02:05:49.680 --> 02:05:55.920
[Guest 2]: conflict is about how military power still matters, you know, so sharpening the military instrument,

02:05:55.920 --> 02:06:02.000
[Guest 2]: regardless of your economic power is also important. Now, having said that, let's look at

02:06:02.000 --> 02:06:06.240
[Guest 2]: economic power and military power. What is the difference? Why is it important, right?

02:06:06.240 --> 02:06:12.720
[Guest 2]: So one thing is that in international relations, we always talk about the idea of fungibility of

02:06:12.720 --> 02:06:18.960
[Guest 2]: power. So this is a concept by David Baldwin, the idea that, you know, you can convert one form of

02:06:18.960 --> 02:06:24.000
[Guest 2]: power to the other, right? So the in that sense, economic power is important. So there was this

02:06:24.000 --> 02:06:29.840
[Guest 2]: study by Paul Kennedy is a historian who looked at great powers over the last 300 400 years,

02:06:29.840 --> 02:06:35.520
[Guest 2]: what was the relationship between economic might and military might. So he sort of concludes that

02:06:35.520 --> 02:06:41.040
[Guest 2]: economic power produces military power, and military power is used to acquire or protect

02:06:41.040 --> 02:06:46.160
[Guest 2]: that economic power, you know, so there is a sort of a spiral arrangement you can think of where

02:06:46.160 --> 02:06:50.800
[Guest 2]: economic power helps you to produce military power, and then military power is used to acquire,

02:06:50.800 --> 02:06:55.920
[Guest 2]: protect, so on and so forth, you keep gaining this over time, right? Now, there is there are

02:06:55.920 --> 02:07:02.720
[Guest 2]: also bounds to this, if too much of economic power is diverted to the military, right up front, then,

02:07:02.720 --> 02:07:07.520
[Guest 2]: you know, your economic might decreases, you don't produce enough productive resources

02:07:07.520 --> 02:07:12.800
[Guest 2]: to be able to improve your might over time, right? And conversely, if there is a lot of

02:07:12.800 --> 02:07:19.120
[Guest 2]: overstretch on the military side, then your economic power also declines, because you have

02:07:19.120 --> 02:07:24.160
[Guest 2]: taken up challenges that you are not ready for, like it has happened with the case of Russia,

02:07:24.160 --> 02:07:29.360
[Guest 2]: right? So now, there is a sort of a military stretch where you have applied military power

02:07:29.360 --> 02:07:35.520
[Guest 2]: beyond your means. And now, the nation states which can respond are responding in the economic

02:07:35.520 --> 02:07:41.840
[Guest 2]: domain, right? So one of the sort of corollaries of this fungibility of power is that a problem

02:07:41.840 --> 02:07:46.880
[Guest 2]: in one domain can be addressed through the application of power in another domain, right?

02:07:46.880 --> 02:07:52.640
[Guest 2]: And that's what you're seeing now that militarily, the West wouldn't want to provoke sort of a

02:07:52.640 --> 02:07:58.800
[Guest 2]: nuclear risk, because they both are nuclear power. So there is a risk in going in that direction.

02:07:58.800 --> 02:08:04.960
[Guest 2]: But economic sphere is where the West does have a lot of power, and it can apply it in direct means

02:08:04.960 --> 02:08:10.640
[Guest 2]: in indirect means. So direct means would be like sanctions, right? There are export controls now

02:08:10.640 --> 02:08:16.080
[Guest 2]: being thought of, even investment controls, investment barriers will be there. Then there

02:08:16.080 --> 02:08:22.560
[Guest 2]: are also means through the international system, right? So WTO, what happens in the trade system

02:08:22.560 --> 02:08:28.160
[Guest 2]: there? How is Russia treated, like you mentioned about SWIFT, etc, right? So there are global

02:08:28.160 --> 02:08:32.880
[Guest 2]: economic systems where you can influence what Russia can do and what you cannot do, right?

02:08:32.880 --> 02:08:40.560
[Guest 2]: So now, what you're seeing unfold is that the West applying power in a dimension they are

02:08:40.560 --> 02:08:46.400
[Guest 2]: more comfortable with, and where Russia is weak, relatively weak. Military power in Ukraine was

02:08:46.400 --> 02:08:51.440
[Guest 2]: its strength, so it could do a lot of things. But now you're seeing the US and the West get

02:08:51.440 --> 02:08:56.960
[Guest 2]: together and apply pressure in that dimension, right? So that's how economic power operates.

02:08:56.960 --> 02:09:03.200
[Guest 2]: Now, obviously, there are fallouts, there are negative consequences of each of these, right? So

02:09:03.200 --> 02:09:10.480
[Guest 2]: military power, one sort of relative advantage is that it can pose an existential threat and can

02:09:10.480 --> 02:09:17.040
[Guest 2]: influence decisions in a very quick time. And this is what General Menon always reminds us when he

02:09:17.040 --> 02:09:22.080
[Guest 2]: teaches his sessions in defense and foreign affairs that, you know, military powers advantages that it

02:09:22.080 --> 02:09:27.680
[Guest 2]: can pose an existential threat in a very limited timeframe. Whereas the effects of economic

02:09:28.320 --> 02:09:33.760
[Guest 2]: sanctions or economic power are over time, one in building your own strength. And second,

02:09:33.760 --> 02:09:39.760
[Guest 2]: if you want to directly use it in a conflict, you have to be immensely more powerful than your

02:09:39.760 --> 02:09:45.040
[Guest 2]: adversary. Now, so that's where you saw in terms of economic power, right? So there are lots of

02:09:45.040 --> 02:09:51.040
[Guest 2]: these measurements about how much bigger power you should be for sanctions to have a coercive

02:09:51.040 --> 02:09:55.280
[Guest 2]: or a deterrent effect. And they are like you need to have an economy which is 100x,

02:09:55.280 --> 02:09:59.680
[Guest 2]: some people argue in order to actually have the kind of deterrent effect that you want,

02:09:59.680 --> 02:10:04.560
[Guest 2]: which was clearly not the case in this conflict, right? Russia is still a big power. So economic

02:10:04.560 --> 02:10:10.560
[Guest 2]: sanctions in a sense didn't work as well as a deterrent. But what economic power can do in this

02:10:10.560 --> 02:10:18.000
[Guest 2]: conflict is to reduce Russia's economic power over time. And then because of the economic power

02:10:18.000 --> 02:10:22.720
[Guest 2]: reducing Russia's military power will also reduce over time, right? If you have very limited

02:10:22.720 --> 02:10:28.160
[Guest 2]: resources, you're not able to buy the best kind of equipments, collaborate with the best kind of

02:10:28.160 --> 02:10:35.120
[Guest 2]: researchers across the world, it will hurt your ability to produce weaponry to even what they

02:10:35.120 --> 02:10:40.320
[Guest 2]: can't even sell to some of the buyers now, right? Because of these sanctions, there will be a

02:10:40.320 --> 02:10:45.840
[Guest 2]: deterrent effect on that. So it will hurt their military power also over time, right? So the idea

02:10:45.840 --> 02:10:52.480
[Guest 2]: is economic power can be used in this way, but its effect will not be as instantaneous as military

02:10:52.480 --> 02:10:58.960
[Guest 2]: powers was and what you saw playing out, right? So this is one way of thinking. The next also like

02:10:58.960 --> 02:11:05.520
[Guest 2]: this concept of power itself is very ambiguous. There are lots and lots of papers and careers made

02:11:05.520 --> 02:11:11.920
[Guest 2]: on thinking about power in international relations. But one sort of measure that I like is

02:11:13.120 --> 02:11:19.120
[Guest 2]: by this political scientist, Mike Beckley, who talks about power of countries should not be

02:11:19.120 --> 02:11:25.360
[Guest 2]: thought of as you can accumulate it over time with no cost. So he thinks of power as a ledger.

02:11:25.360 --> 02:11:32.080
[Guest 2]: No, there are costs ledger where you also have some costs that you have to incur and also benefits

02:11:32.080 --> 02:11:37.040
[Guest 2]: that you incur. So if in that ledger formulation, power can be thought of as for example,

02:11:37.040 --> 02:11:43.440
[Guest 2]: population, population is also on the positive side. And it also can be on the negative side

02:11:43.440 --> 02:11:48.640
[Guest 2]: in the sense that you also have to provide for a larger amount of population etc. And

02:11:48.640 --> 02:11:53.920
[Guest 2]: definitely it's on the positive side because after all people give a lot of benefit, right?

02:11:53.920 --> 02:11:59.680
[Guest 2]: So if you look at that formulation, he thinks of power as you can predict outcomes of a lot

02:11:59.680 --> 02:12:07.600
[Guest 2]: of great power rivalries if you think of power as GDP multiplied by GDP per capita. So this is

02:12:07.600 --> 02:12:14.320
[Guest 2]: a rough again a model but which says that if a country's power is determined by this formulation,

02:12:14.320 --> 02:12:19.520
[Guest 2]: then you are able to predict even the outcomes of great power rivalries well and it has he does

02:12:19.520 --> 02:12:25.120
[Guest 2]: this over last five or six rivalries over 200-300 years in order to get this. Now this is an

02:12:25.120 --> 02:12:30.880
[Guest 2]: interesting formulation because GDP represents sort of the benefit side, right? The more the

02:12:30.880 --> 02:12:36.560
[Guest 2]: bigger the country will have the bigger the GDP, whereas GDP per capita also takes into account

02:12:36.560 --> 02:12:43.200
[Guest 2]: the costs of providing for a larger population, whether you are able to have enough growth so

02:12:43.200 --> 02:12:50.400
[Guest 2]: that you are able to also increase the productivity of every individual, right? So that so if you look

02:12:50.400 --> 02:12:55.520
[Guest 2]: at this formulation, it is interesting, right? GDP, India's GDP is big, but when you do GDP

02:12:55.520 --> 02:13:01.360
[Guest 2]: into GDP per capita, we might be in the middle income range, right? So that sort of is a good

02:13:01.360 --> 02:13:07.040
[Guest 2]: formulation to think of power in international relations and it takes into account economic

02:13:07.040 --> 02:13:12.400
[Amit Varma]: power and its impact on military power as well. So one of the points you made was that you know

02:13:12.400 --> 02:13:16.480
[Amit Varma]: that when we talk about the fungibility of power like this that a problem in one domain can be

02:13:16.480 --> 02:13:21.520
[Amit Varma]: addressed in another. Now it just strikes me that if I'm Putin and I'm sitting there and I

02:13:21.520 --> 02:13:25.760
[Amit Varma]: see your economic power and I see what the sanctions will do and it will lead to a vicious

02:13:25.760 --> 02:13:30.400
[Amit Varma]: circle where I'll get economically affected and therefore I'll get militarily affected because

02:13:30.400 --> 02:13:35.920
[Amit Varma]: you know I have less to invest in building up my arms and so on and it's a it's a spiral to

02:13:35.920 --> 02:13:41.440
[Amit Varma]: the bottom and I can't win. So why would he not then bring his nuclear put his nuclear weapons

02:13:41.440 --> 02:13:46.560
[Amit Varma]: back on the table and say that fine you know since it's you know shift the focus from one domain to

02:13:46.560 --> 02:13:51.120
[Amit Varma]: other and say that fine economic sanctions fine I'm crazy you know play the good game theorist

02:13:51.120 --> 02:13:55.200
[Amit Varma]: would call the game of chicken and you know whether or not he is actually rational but

02:13:55.200 --> 02:14:00.000
[Amit Varma]: it's rational for him to play that game and to give the impression that he can do anything and

02:14:00.000 --> 02:14:05.360
[Amit Varma]: so if nuclear weapons come on the table then doesn't that kind of balance the whole economic

02:14:05.360 --> 02:14:09.520
[Amit Varma]: power equation I mean the the you mentioned General Menon I recorded that excellent episode

02:14:09.520 --> 02:14:13.840
[Amit Varma]: where he gave me so much insight on India going nuclear and all of that and one of the things that

02:14:13.840 --> 02:14:18.240
[Amit Varma]: India going nuclear obviously did was that it actually brought India on par with Pakistan

02:14:18.800 --> 02:14:23.120
[Amit Varma]: or rather brought Pakistan on par with India because they both got nuclear weapons and

02:14:23.120 --> 02:14:28.240
[Amit Varma]: therefore any engagement they have has to be a super superbly limited engagement because

02:14:28.240 --> 02:14:34.400
[Amit Varma]: neither side can afford an escalation and while we in terms of conventional army at that time we

02:14:34.400 --> 02:14:38.480
[Amit Varma]: would have had a massive superiority suddenly we were equal because both sides have a nuclear

02:14:38.480 --> 02:14:44.080
[Amit Varma]: weapon so similarly I would imagine that putting the nuclear option on the table would be one way

02:14:44.080 --> 02:14:52.960
[Amit Varma]: for Putin to reduce the asymmetry otherwise yeah so absolutely like nuclear powers addition of

02:14:52.960 --> 02:14:58.000
[Guest 2]: nuclear weapons sort of gives you an offset right you can suddenly bridge some of the gaps

02:14:58.000 --> 02:15:02.800
[Guest 2]: that you could but put Putin has already brought nuclear weapons to the table right he's already

02:15:02.800 --> 02:15:08.160
[Guest 2]: mentioned that if any country were to intervene they will have consequences which you have never

02:15:08.160 --> 02:15:14.720
[Guest 2]: heard of and things like that so that thing has already passed after that is where these economic

02:15:14.720 --> 02:15:20.880
[Guest 2]: sanctions have been improved and of course he can say what he wants to say but the consequences of

02:15:20.880 --> 02:15:28.240
[Guest 2]: nuclear escalation will be felt by him by Russia at large as well right so it's not as if you can

02:15:28.240 --> 02:15:33.600
[Guest 2]: the bluster is fine but for for you to act you know that there is the consequences only one

02:15:33.600 --> 02:15:39.840
[Guest 2]: and that's annihilation so how long can you play that game of chicken right that is one before that

02:15:39.840 --> 02:15:44.800
[Guest 2]: I would say that actually what Putin did because of this economic sanctions and knowing that

02:15:44.800 --> 02:15:50.640
[Guest 2]: economic power is the western is that they tried to isolate themselves gain more economic power

02:15:50.640 --> 02:15:57.200
[Guest 2]: over the last four five years right so if you read many articles on this there were this idea of

02:15:57.200 --> 02:16:02.960
[Guest 2]: building their foreign exchange reserves also this idea of they knew that they are connected

02:16:02.960 --> 02:16:09.600
[Guest 2]: with Europe because of the gas connection energy so there are only certain things that the west

02:16:09.600 --> 02:16:14.480
[Guest 2]: can do without incurring costs on their own citizens so that calculation was also there

02:16:14.480 --> 02:16:20.000
[Guest 2]: because the sanctions game is actually quite old so he tried to make sure that generally they are

02:16:20.000 --> 02:16:25.920
[Guest 2]: shielded from the effects of another sanction of the kind that had happened earlier I guess

02:16:25.920 --> 02:16:31.360
[Guest 2]: the difference this time is that the current sanctions are like unprecedented in scope

02:16:31.360 --> 02:16:38.080
[Guest 2]: earlier you had sanctions from US etc but US and Russia don't trade much anyways but this time

02:16:38.080 --> 02:16:44.960
[Guest 2]: because of how abhorrent this invasion is being seen there are not just sanctions there are

02:16:44.960 --> 02:16:51.760
[Guest 2]: secondary sanctions and you know sanctions of the kind that if you are a supplier to Russian

02:16:52.400 --> 02:16:58.240
[Guest 2]: military or say Russian strategic establishment and you just buy some equipment from the US

02:16:58.240 --> 02:17:03.040
[Guest 2]: these sanctions also apply to you you know so that's like the kind of sanctions which we generally

02:17:03.040 --> 02:17:08.880
[Guest 2]: don't see and which are very difficult to enforce actually but this is what has been attempted and

02:17:08.880 --> 02:17:15.360
[Guest 2]: there is a lot of overwhelming support from a lot of countries on this which makes it difficult for

02:17:15.360 --> 02:17:21.360
[Guest 2]: Russia to sort of sidestep this you know so there is real cost like you were saying on Russian

02:17:21.360 --> 02:17:26.320
[Guest 2]: citizens also because of this even though the sanctions are tried they have tried to craft it

02:17:26.320 --> 02:17:33.280
[Guest 2]: in a way that they don't affect the common person but I think the effect will still be felt by a lot

02:17:33.280 --> 02:17:39.520
[Guest 2]: of people so essentially if you are buying anything which is to do with Russian military if you are a

02:17:39.520 --> 02:17:45.040
[Guest 2]: company which deals with the Russian military in any way or say data centers that are owned by the

02:17:45.040 --> 02:17:50.800
[Guest 2]: Russian government you sort of come into the ambit of this sanction if you are buying something which

02:17:50.800 --> 02:17:56.000
[Guest 2]: is significantly American which is pretty much everything a lot of things will be American so

02:17:56.000 --> 02:18:01.280
[Guest 2]: that's why these economic sanctions have are a new thing in that sense you know they are

02:18:01.280 --> 02:18:06.560
[Guest 2]: unprecedented in scope and let's see how that plays out so I don't think it will sort of

02:18:06.560 --> 02:18:13.280
[Guest 2]: necessarily lead to toppling of the regime or etc but there's genuinely a pressure which it

02:18:13.280 --> 02:18:20.240
[Guest 2]: puts and probably reduces economic power over time even if this war ends in two three days

02:18:20.240 --> 02:18:26.960
[Guest 2]: the sanctions are not very easily they won't go away very easily there will be this

02:18:26.960 --> 02:18:31.360
[Guest 2]: impact of reducing economic power and reducing military power over time.

02:18:33.040 --> 02:18:37.520
[Amit Varma]: So you know you referred to Putin's nuclear rhetoric as bluster and you said how long can

02:18:37.520 --> 02:18:42.240
[Amit Varma]: he play the game of chicken and you were laughing and part of the sort of implication of that was

02:18:42.800 --> 02:18:48.000
[Amit Varma]: in the end we are all rational people the cost is too much but could it be the case that foreign

02:18:48.000 --> 02:18:55.120
[Amit Varma]: policy may sort of foreign policy perhaps doesn't adequately take into account the fact that humans

02:18:55.120 --> 02:19:00.880
[Amit Varma]: can be irrational frail even insane I mean if you kind of look back into the 1930s and you talk

02:19:00.880 --> 02:19:05.520
[Amit Varma]: about Hitler for example you know you may not take into account how far he will go because a lot of

02:19:05.520 --> 02:19:11.200
[Amit Varma]: it is irrational you know if at some point people were to hear about plans of the holocaust they

02:19:11.200 --> 02:19:16.880
[Amit Varma]: would surely discount it they would say it is not rational for anybody to do something so monstrous

02:19:16.880 --> 02:19:22.160
[Amit Varma]: but the point is he went out and did it and the thing is foreign policy can largely treat people

02:19:22.160 --> 02:19:27.360
[Amit Varma]: as rational actors but you only need to be wrong once you know for the kind of annihilation that

02:19:27.360 --> 02:19:32.800
